(1) XB-1 First Supersonic Flight
From Boom Supersonic
The successful first supersonic flight of Boom=E2=80=99s demonstrator aircr=
aft, XB-1, took place on January 28 2025 at the Mojave Air & Space Port in =
California. Boom designed, built, and flew the world=E2=80=99s first indepe=
ndently developed supersonic jet=E2=80=94the first civil supersonic jet mad=
e in America.
We are once again a Supersonic Civilization.
On Tuesday, Boom Supersonic=E2=80=99s XB-1 demonstrator aircraft broke the =
sound barrier during a test flight at Mojave Air & Space Port. The XB-1, pi=
loted by Chief Test Pilot Tristan "Geppetto" Brandenburg (great name), reac=
hed an altitude of 35,290 feet and accelerated to Mach 1.122 (750 mph), mar=
king the first time a privately developed civil supersonic jet has achieved=
 supersonic speeds.
Boom=E2=80=99s XB-1 demonstrator aircraft and its demonstration of going su=
personic, is a major milestone for the company=E2=80=99s ultimate mission o=
f making commercial aircraft travel supersonic. The company=E2=80=99s plann=
ed Overture airliner aims to have capacity for 60-80 passengers and travel =
at speeds of Mach 1.7, or 1,300 mph. Overture should be able to travel twic=
e as fast overwater and 20% as fast overland as traditional commercial airl=
iners. That would cut down the time it takes to fly from New York to London=
 from about seven hours to approximately three and a half hours. The compan=
y has already secured 130 pre-orders for its supersonic airliners from the =
likes of American Airlines, United, and Japan Airlines.
Boom.=20
(2) DeepSeek-R1: Incentivizing Reasoning Capability in LLMs via Reinforceme=
nt Learning [ https://substack.com/redirect/105e5368-ae65-4daf-a2ae-12b1c29=
4e9d7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From DeepSeek
We introduce our first-generation reasoning models, DeepSeek-R1-Zero and De=
epSeek-R1. DeepSeek-R1-Zero, a model trained via large-scale reinforcement =
learning (RL) without super- vised fine-tuning (SFT) as a preliminary step,=
 demonstrates remarkable reasoning capabilities.
If I had a nickel for every DeepSeek hot take I=E2=80=99ve read over the pa=
st week, I could train DeepSeek.
We don=E2=80=99t really have a hot take, but I think there are probably som=
e takeaways from the whole ordeal:
It=E2=80=99s turns out you can train a best-in-class AI model for way less =
than you=E2=80=99ve had to in the past. DeepSeek is marketing that it spent=
 $5.5M to train R1, but that is likely an underestimation of the true costs=
, let alone the cost is was able to forgo by building on (and training on) =
the models that came before it. Whatever the true cost, it was surprisingly=
 cheap and that=E2=80=99s going to drive costs down in the rest of the indu=
stry.
Open sourcing leads to commodization and, likely, a faster pace of innovati=
on. Going forward, there will still be frontier breakthroughs, but those br=
eakthroughs will likely be quickly copied and open sourced. That=E2=80=99ll=
 drive down the prices to use AI models and that will mean we can use AI to=
 do more things that otherwise wouldn=E2=80=99t be economically logical.
We=E2=80=99ll likely see Jevons Paradox play out at massive scale. Jevons P=
aradox is the idea that increasing efficiency in resource use often leads t=
o higher overall consumption of that resource, rather than a reduction. Eve=
ryone is freaking out about how DeepSeek impacts future Nvidia demand, but =
Jevons would lead you to believe that training AI models get more cost effi=
cient, the demand for chips will actually increase. This is especially true=
 for Nvidia, which now does a much higher percentage of its revenue from in=
ference: as models get cheaper and AI usage increases, inference needs will=
 increase ~linearly. The training business may be in some trouble, but that=
 trouble may be offset from a massive wave of demand for inference.
Sam Altman is now basically running a DTC brand at OpenAI. In DTC, it=E2=80=
=99s hard to differentiate on product and channels for acquiring new custom=
ers are becoming saturated and less efficient. On the product side, once th=
ere are signs of traction, your product gets copy catted out of the wazoo =
=E2=80=94 both from legitimate competitors and Chinese dupers. On the acqui=
sition front, overtime the value accrues to who is able to generate attenti=
on and demand. In traditional DTC, that=E2=80=99s Meta, Google, and Amazon.=
 It=E2=80=99s not yet quite exactly clear where value will accrue in user a=
cquisition in AI. Ultimately, the only way to differentiate or win long-ter=
m is to build a brand that people trust or feel compelled to talk about. Sa=
m if you need some advise on running a DTC brand, feel free to shoot me a t=
ext.
(3) Science Corp. Aims to Plant Ideas in Brains with New Device [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/91414171-2420-4c24-ac8a-0384c24c1c67?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance for Core Memory
Near the end of last year, Science revealed its work [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/be14f571-97a9-4eb6-981d-33d655f28ae7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on technology that makes it possib=
le to fuse large quantities of lab-grown neurons with an animal=E2=80=99s b=
rain. To do this, Science has built a device that preserves the manufacture=
d neurons in a gel. It then takes out part of an animal=E2=80=99s skull and=
 places its device atop the animal=E2=80=99s brain. In the days that follow=
, the neurons in the device begin to develop wiring that stretches out from=
 Science=E2=80=99s hardware and into the brain, giving the animal access to=
 extra stores of mental horsepower.
Science Corp [ https://substack.com/redirect/7367af67-5dc2-4eb3-8826-1e1039=
36db53?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 got the Ashlee Vance treatment.
The company, led by Neuralink cofounder Max Hodak, is pioneering a new kind=
 of brain-computer interface (BCI) that fuses lab-grown neurons with an ani=
mal's brain using a neuron-rich gel device (see above) placed atop the skul=
l. Unlike traditional implants that target specific brain regions, its "bio=
hybrid neural interfaces" aim to integrate seamlessly, providing general-pu=
rpose cognitive enhancement without deep brain penetration or genetic modif=
ications.
The company early experiments in mice suggest that it could help repair neu=
ral damage by rerouting signals around compromised tissue, and early use ca=
ses will focus on righting damages to the brain, but according to Hodak, =
=E2=80=9CThe really interesting stuff is how do we go from, like, closing y=
our eyes and imagining a scene to copying that to a computer. You can just =
imagine a sound and then download it. We think that may be possible.=E2=80=
=9D
Go Duke [ https://substack.com/redirect/3a7af539-4c7c-4ee9-8139-88a7d4f4daa=
4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(Sidenote: it=E2=80=99s great to have Ashlee Vance [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/bcc391db-9fe6-45ac-b0a5-f324d99c178a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] unleashed with his new media company=
, Core Memory. On Wednesday, he dropped a profile on HudZah [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/60c51dc6-2c79-4d10-8c09-2e49cfbaeaa1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=94 the Waterloo stud=
ent who used AI to make a nuclear fusor in his house =E2=80=94 that just ma=
kes you excited for the future and envious of the youths. What a time to be=
 alive.)=20
(4) Engineered heart muscle allografts for heart repair in primates and hum=
ans [ https://substack.com/redirect/a0240b22-c7e1-4893-b566-932534560a05?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Jebran et al in Nature
In the heart failure model, evidence for EHM allograft-enhanced target hear=
t wall contractility and ejection fraction, which are measures for local an=
d global heart support, was obtained. Histopathological and gadolinium-base=
d perfusion magnetic resonance imaging analyses confirmed cell retention an=
d functional vascularization. Arrhythmia and tumour growth were not observe=
d. The obtained feasibility, safety and efficacy data provided the pivotal =
underpinnings for the approval of a first-in-human clinical trial on tissue=
-engineered heart repair. Our clinical data confirmed remuscularization by =
EHM implantation in a patient with advanced heart failure.
One personal story. One macro stat.
Personal: When I was two years old, I had open heart surgery to repair an a=
trial septal defect. It was a pretty massive surgery to conduct on a very s=
mall body, and was quite risky back in the mid-90s. I=E2=80=99ve been scare=
d of and interested in heart stuff ever since.
Macro: Heart disease is the leading cause of death in the U.S., killing one=
 person every 33 seconds=E2=80=94more than all forms of cancer combined. Tu=
rns out the heart is a very, very important organ. So advancements in cardi=
ovascular research can have a massive impact. Which is why this research in=
 Nature caught my eye.
Researchers created engineered heart muscle (EHM) grafts from stem cells to=
 repair failing hearts. In initial trials on monkeys, these grafts integrat=
ed well, improved heart function, and showed no major side effects. A human=
 trial also showed successful heart remuscularization in a patient with adv=
anced heart failure. The ability to successfully and scalable repair failin=
g hearts offers a potential alternative to the 10,000+ full heart transplan=
ts that occur each year globally.
(5) "New Space" (Frontier Film Trailer) [ https://substack.com/redirect/80a=
75616-215b-41fb-bf34-583e5eeb845e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Friend of the newsletter, Jason Carman, is releasing his first feature leng=
th film =E2=80=9CNew Space=E2=80=9D tomorrow evening. The movie is near 90 =
minutes long, features over 20 interviews with space leaders from industry =
and government, and chronicles the story of space today. If the full-length=
 version is anything like the trailer, I won=E2=80=99t be able to look away=
=2E Seriously, watch that trailer and t=
ry not to get pumped up. Follow the S3=
 Youtube channel [ https://substack.com/redirect/e3a5c06d-f353-4413-a0ec-a1=
4559f7cb35?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] and turn on your notis for Jason on X [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
c234c51f-35c2-490e-bb11-9492af5847ef?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] so you don=E2=80=99t miss the drop.
At Not Boring, we=E2=80=99ve written extensively on what=E2=80=99s happenin=
g in the space industry today. We cover it weekly and Packy has written mul=
tiple short books on the industry and its emergent players over the years. =
Reading all of that (here [ https://substack.com/redirect/d9ed1a78-6c93-4e5=
6-a650-5338252a3afb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], here [ https://substack.com/redirect/10b88b45-c958-4990-a92e=
-b342a2cee584?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ], here [ https://substack.com/redirect/cfa71c27-7d2e-4155-9473-66395=
41a6353?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
], and here [ https://substack.com/redirect/5afbb4c1-745a-4e3d-a26c-148a12f=
bad45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ])=
 is great, but watching it all come to life in an epic 90 minute video may =
be even cooler.
Bonus:
Meter is building the "internet utility"=E2=80=94a vertically integrated ne=
tworking company that aims to make setting up and managing internet infrast=
ructure as seamless as turning on electricity or water. This is one of the =
most impressive companies you=E2=80=99ve never heard of. And Packy covered =
